üé• Episode 0 ‚Äî Series Introduction: Building a Hotel Booking System with Spring Cloud
1. Narration Script (spoken style)
Intro (on camera):

Hey everyone, welcome to this brand-new tutorial series on Spring Cloud.
Over the next several episodes, we‚Äôre going to build something real ‚Äî a Hotel Booking System ‚Äî using microservices and the full Spring Cloud ecosystem.
By the end of this series, you‚Äôll understand not only the concepts, but also how to build and run a complete distributed system with Spring Boot and Spring Cloud.

Why Spring Cloud (voice-over with slide):

So why Spring Cloud?
When we move from a monolith to microservices, we face challenges like:

How do services discover each other?

How do we manage configuration across dozens of services?

How do we handle failures gracefully?

And how do we trace a single user request as it flows across multiple services?

Spring Cloud gives us tools to solve all of these problems ‚Äî from service discovery, to load balancing, to centralized config, to distributed tracing.

The real-world case study (on camera + diagram):

Instead of just talking theory, we‚Äôll build a Hotel Booking System.
Here‚Äôs the scenario:

Users can search hotels, book rooms, make payments, and receive booking confirmations.

Behind the scenes, multiple microservices will work together to make that possible.

(Show architecture diagram on screen: Hotel Service, Booking Service, Payment Service, Notification Service, User Service, plus Config Server, Eureka, and API Gateway.)

Services Overview (voice-over + diagram zoom-ins):

We‚Äôll implement:

A Hotel Service for hotels and room availability.

A Booking Service for reservations and cancellations.

A Payment Service for processing payments.

A Notification Service to send booking confirmations.

And a User Service to handle authentication and profiles.

On top of that, we‚Äôll add supporting infrastructure:

Eureka for service discovery,

Spring Cloud Gateway for routing requests,

Spring Cloud Config for centralized configuration,

Sleuth and Zipkin for distributed tracing,

and Resilience4j for circuit breaking and fault tolerance.

What you‚Äôll learn (on camera):

So what‚Äôs in it for you?
You‚Äôll learn not just how to use Spring Cloud, but also why each part is important.
We‚Äôll cover both the classic Netflix stack ‚Äî things like Ribbon and Hystrix ‚Äî and the modern Spring Cloud stack with LoadBalancer and Resilience4j.
That way, you‚Äôll understand the old tutorials you see online, but also know how to build new systems with the recommended tools.

Demo (screen share):

In today‚Äôs intro episode, we‚Äôll just make sure our environment is ready.
I‚Äôll be using Java 17, Spring Boot 3.5, and Spring Cloud 2025 release train.
You‚Äôll also need Docker for some parts, like running Zipkin or spinning up our stack with docker-compose.
In the next episode, we‚Äôll set up our multi-module Maven project and get the basics running.

(Show your IDE open, with empty project structure ready. Maybe a hotel-booking-system/ folder with submodules prepared.)

