üé• Episode 1 ‚Äî Project Setup & First Microservice
1. Narration Script (spoken style)
Intro (on camera):

Welcome back! In this first coding episode, we‚Äôre going to set up our project.
We‚Äôll create a multi-module Maven project for our Hotel Booking System, bring in Spring Boot and Spring Cloud dependencies, and scaffold our very first microservice.
This is the foundation we‚Äôll build everything else on.

Concept Explanation (with slide):

In a microservices system, each service ‚Äî like Hotel, Booking, or Payment ‚Äî is its own Spring Boot application.
But since they share some common dependencies, we‚Äôll manage them with a parent Maven project.
This makes it easier to keep all services consistent, especially when we upgrade Spring Boot or Spring Cloud versions.

(Show slide: diagram of parent POM at top, services underneath ‚Äî Hotel, Booking, Payment, etc.)

We‚Äôll be using:

Java 17 (required for Spring Boot 3.x).

Spring Boot 3.5.x.

Spring Cloud 2025.0.0 release train.

Demo Part 1 ‚Äî Parent Project (IDE + terminal):

Let‚Äôs create our project folder called hotel-booking-system.
Inside, we‚Äôll create a parent pom.xml that defines the Spring Boot and Spring Cloud versions.

<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 
                             http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <groupId>com.example</groupId>
  <artifactId>hotel-booking-system</artifactId>
  <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  <packaging>pom</packaging>

  <modules>
    <module>hotel-service</module>
    <module>booking-service</module>
    <module>payment-service</module>
    <module>notification-service</module>
    <module>user-service</module>
  </modules>

  <properties>
    <java.version>17</java.version>
    <spring-boot.version>3.5.5</spring-boot.version>
    <spring-cloud.version>2025.0.0</spring-cloud.version>
  </properties>

  <parent>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-parent</artifactId>
    <version>${spring-boot.version}</version>
    <relativePath/>
  </parent>

  <dependencyManagement>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-cloud-dependencies</artifactId>
        <version>${spring-cloud.version}</version>
        <type>pom</type>
        <scope>import</scope>
      </dependency>
    </dependencies>
  </dependencyManagement>
</project>
Demo Part 2 ‚Äî First Service (Hotel Service):

Next, let‚Äôs scaffold our Hotel Service.
We create a folder hotel-service with its own pom.xml.

<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 
                             http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <parent>
    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>hotel-booking-system</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>hotel-service</artifactId>

  <dependencies>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
      <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-web</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
      <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-actuator</artifactId>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>
</project>
Demo Part 3 ‚Äî Simple Controller:

Now let‚Äôs add a very simple REST controller, just to prove it works.

@SpringBootApplication
public class HotelServiceApplication {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    SpringApplication.run(HotelServiceApplication.class, args);
  }
}

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/hotels")
class HotelController {
  @GetMapping
  public List<String> getHotels() {
    return List.of("Grand Palace", "Seaside Resort", "Mountain Inn");
  }
}
Demo Part 4 ‚Äî Run & Test:

Let‚Äôs run the Hotel Service.
In IntelliJ or with Maven: mvn spring-boot:run -pl hotel-service.
Now in the browser, go to http://localhost:8080/hotels.
And there we go ‚Äî our first microservice is alive!

(Show browser with JSON response: [ "Grand Palace", "Seaside Resort", "Mountain Inn" ])

Recap (on camera):

That‚Äôs it for Episode 1!
Today we:

Set up a multi-module Maven project,

Created a parent POM with Spring Boot and Spring Cloud dependencies,

And built our very first microservice ‚Äî the Hotel Service.

In the next episode, we‚Äôll set up Spring Cloud Config so all our services can share centralized configuration.
Stay tuned, and don‚Äôt forget to subscribe!

