üé• Episode 3 ‚Äî Service Discovery with Eureka
1. Narration Script (spoken style)
Intro (on camera):

Welcome back! In the last episode, we set up centralized configuration with Spring Cloud Config.
Today, we‚Äôre going to tackle one of the most important concepts in microservices: service discovery.
And we‚Äôll implement it using Eureka from Spring Cloud Netflix.

Concept Explanation (with slide):

Imagine you have multiple services running ‚Äî Hotel Service, Booking Service, Payment Service.
How do they know each other‚Äôs IP address or port?
We could hardcode URLs‚Ä¶ but in a dynamic environment where services scale up and down, that quickly becomes painful.

(Show slide: Problem diagram ‚Äî Booking Service calls Hotel Service via hardcoded URL, but instance changes.)

The solution is service discovery.
Each service registers itself with a central Eureka Server.
Then, other services can find it just by its name, not by IP or port.
Think of it like a phonebook for microservices.

(Show slide: Eureka server in the middle, services registering and looking each other up.)

Demo Part 1 ‚Äî Setting up Eureka Server:

Let‚Äôs create a new module called eureka-server inside our project.
In the pom.xml, we‚Äôll add the Eureka server starter.

<dependencies>
  <dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-server</artifactId>
  </dependency>
</dependencies>
Then in the main class, we enable the Eureka server:

@SpringBootApplication
@EnableEurekaServer
public class EurekaServerApplication {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    SpringApplication.run(EurekaServerApplication.class, args);
  }
}
And in application.yml:

server:
  port: 8761

spring:
  application:
    name: eureka-server

eureka:
  client:
    register-with-eureka: false
    fetch-registry: false
Let‚Äôs run it.
Open http://localhost:8761 and you should see the Eureka dashboard ‚Äî right now it‚Äôs empty.

Demo Part 2 ‚Äî Registering Hotel Service as Eureka Client:

Now, let‚Äôs make our Hotel Service register with Eureka.
In its pom.xml, add the Eureka client starter:

<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-client</artifactId>
</dependency>
Then in application.yml for Hotel Service:

spring:
  application:
    name: hotel-service

server:
  port: 8081

eureka:
  client:
    service-url:
      defaultZone: http://localhost:8761/eureka/
That‚Äôs it ‚Äî just by adding the dependency and configuration, the service auto-registers with Eureka.

Demo Part 3 ‚Äî Registering Booking Service:

Let‚Äôs do the same for Booking Service.
Its application.yml might look like this:

spring:
  application:
    name: booking-service

server:
  port: 8082

eureka:
  client:
    service-url:
      defaultZone: http://localhost:8761/eureka/
Now restart both services, refresh the Eureka dashboard ‚Äî
and you‚Äôll see HOTEL-SERVICE and BOOKING-SERVICE listed as registered instances.

Demo Part 4 ‚Äî Using Service Discovery:

The real magic is when one service calls another.
Instead of hardcoding http://localhost:8081/hotels,
Booking Service can now use the logical name: http://hotel-service/hotels.
Behind the scenes, Eureka resolves it to the actual instance.
Later, we‚Äôll combine this with load balancing to distribute calls across multiple hotel-service instances.

Recap (on camera):

That‚Äôs it for Episode 3!
Today we:

Learned why service discovery is important in microservices.

Set up a Eureka Server.

Registered Hotel Service and Booking Service as Eureka clients.

And saw how services can now talk to each other using just their names.

In the next episode, we‚Äôll introduce an API Gateway so that clients don‚Äôt talk to microservices directly.
Instead, they‚Äôll go through one entry point that handles routing, security, and cross-cutting concerns.

