You said:
yes
ChatGPT said:
Perfect üëå Let‚Äôs wire up Booking Service ‚Üí Hotel Service call using Eureka discovery.
We‚Äôll do it two ways (both are common in Spring Cloud tutorials):

RestTemplate with @LoadBalanced

OpenFeign (cleaner, declarative)

üîó Step 1: Add Dependencies
In booking-service/pom.xml, add:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-openfeign</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-loadbalancer</artifactId>
</dependency>
üîó Step 2: Enable Feign Clients
BookingServiceApplication.java

package com.example.bookingservice;

import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;
import org.springframework.cloud.openfeign.EnableFeignClients;

@SpringBootApplication
@EnableFeignClients
public class BookingServiceApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(BookingServiceApplication.class, args);
    }
}
üîó Step 3: Create Feign Client to Hotel Service
HotelClient.java

package com.example.bookingservice.client;

import org.springframework.cloud.openfeign.FeignClient;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;

import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

@FeignClient(name = "hotel-service") // serviceId registered in Eureka
public interface HotelClient {

    @GetMapping("/hotels")
    List<Map<String, String>> getHotels();
}
üîó Step 4: Use HotelClient in Booking Service
BookingController.java

package com.example.bookingservice.controller;

import com.example.bookingservice.client.HotelClient;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

@RestController
public class BookingController {

    private final HotelClient hotelClient;

    public BookingController(HotelClient hotelClient) {
        this.hotelClient = hotelClient;
    }

    @GetMapping("/booking/hotels")
    public List<Map<String, String>> getAvailableHotels() {
        // Call hotel-service via Feign (discovered through Eureka)
        return hotelClient.getHotels();
    }

    @GetMapping("/booking/status")
    public Map<String, String> getBookingStatus() {
        return Map.of("status", "Booking service is running");
    }
}
üîó Step 5: Alternative ‚Äì RestTemplate with LoadBalancer
If you also want to show RestTemplate, create a bean:

AppConfig.java

package com.example.bookingservice.config;

import org.springframework.cloud.client.loadbalancer.LoadBalanced;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.web.client.RestTemplate;

@Configuration
public class AppConfig {

    @Bean
    @LoadBalanced  // tells Spring Cloud to resolve service names via Eureka
    public RestTemplate restTemplate() {
        return new RestTemplate();
    }
}
Then in BookingController.java:

@Autowired
private RestTemplate restTemplate;

@GetMapping("/booking/hotels-rest")
public List<Map<String, String>> getHotelsViaRestTemplate() {
    return restTemplate.getForObject("http://hotel-service/hotels", List.class);
}
üöÄ How to Test
Run all three services:

eureka-server ‚Üí http://localhost:8761

hotel-service ‚Üí http://localhost:8081/hotels

booking-service ‚Üí http://localhost:8082/booking/hotels

Go to:

http://localhost:8082/booking/hotels ‚Üí returns hotel list (via Feign + Eureka)

http://localhost:8082/booking/hotels-rest ‚Üí returns hotel list (via RestTemplate + Eureka)

Stop hotel-service ‚Üí Eureka will eventually mark it as DOWN.

Requests from booking-service will start failing.

In the next episode, we‚Äôll add Hystrix / Resilience4j to handle failures gracefully.

‚ú® Now you can showcase actual discovery in action ‚Äî Booking Service doesn‚Äôt know 8081, it just says hotel-service, and Eureka + LoadBalancer handle the rest.

