üé• Episode 6 ‚Äî Distributed Tracing with Sleuth & Zipkin
1. Narration Script (spoken style)
Intro (on camera):

Welcome back! So far, we‚Äôve built a system with multiple microservices ‚Äî Hotel, Booking, Payments, and more.
We‚Äôve added service discovery, load balancing, an API gateway, and even circuit breakers.
But here‚Äôs the challenge: when something goes wrong, how do we debug across multiple services?

If a request fails in Booking Service, was it actually Hotel Service‚Äôs fault? Or maybe Payments timed out?
To solve this, we need distributed tracing.

Concept Explanation (with slides/diagram):

Distributed tracing lets us follow a single request end-to-end across microservices.

Each request gets a unique trace ID.

Each service call adds a span ‚Äî showing how long it took and whether it succeeded or failed.

Tools like Zipkin let us visualize the entire trace as a timeline.

(Slide: show request ‚Üí API Gateway ‚Üí Booking ‚Üí Hotel, all connected by same trace ID.)

In Spring Cloud, we use:

Sleuth ‚Üí automatically generates trace IDs and spans.

Zipkin ‚Üí collects and visualizes tracing data.

Demo Part 1 ‚Äî Add Sleuth & Zipkin Dependencies

In every microservice (hotel-service, booking-service, payment-service, notification-service, user-service), add:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-sleuth</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-zipkin</artifactId>
</dependency>
Demo Part 2 ‚Äî Configure Zipkin

In each service‚Äôs application.yml:

spring:
  zipkin:
    base-url: http://localhost:9411
  sleuth:
    sampler:
      probability: 1.0
base-url ‚Üí tells Sleuth where Zipkin is running.

sampler.probability: 1.0 ‚Üí trace 100% of requests (good for dev; in production maybe 10%).

Demo Part 3 ‚Äî Run Zipkin

Run Zipkin with Docker:

docker run -d -p 9411:9411 openzipkin/zipkin
Zipkin UI ‚Üí http://localhost:9411.

Demo Part 4 ‚Äî Test Distributed Trace

Start all services (Eureka, API Gateway, Hotel, Booking, etc.).

Make a request through API Gateway:

http://localhost:8080/booking-service/booking/hotels
In service logs, you‚Äôll see something like:

[traceId=8f3d1c4f7a12a9e3 spanId=8f3d1c4f7a12a9e3] BookingService --> Calling HotelService
Notice: the traceId is the same across both Booking and Hotel services.

Open Zipkin UI ‚Üí Search traces ‚Üí You‚Äôll see:

API Gateway span

Booking Service span

Hotel Service span

(Show the timeline graph ‚Äî viewers will love this visual!)

Demo Part 5 ‚Äî Simulate a Failure

Kill Hotel Service (like in Episode 5).

Call /booking/hotels again.

In Zipkin timeline, you‚Äôll see:

Booking ‚Üí Hotel call (with error flag)

Fallback response triggered

üé¨ This ties directly back to the circuit breaker demo!

Recap (on camera):

Today we added distributed tracing with Sleuth + Zipkin.
Now, every request gets a trace ID, and we can visualize the entire flow across microservices.

This helps us debug failures.

Measure performance bottlenecks.

Understand how services interact.

