üé• Episode 8 ‚Äî Securing API Gateway with Authentication (User Service + JWT)
1. Narration Script (spoken style)
Intro (on camera):

Welcome back! Right now, anyone can call our Booking, Hotel, or Payment services through the API Gateway ‚Äî no login required.
In a real-world hotel booking system, that‚Äôs a big problem.
We need to make sure only registered users can book hotels, make payments, or view their profiles.

To solve this, we‚Äôll add authentication using our User Service and secure the API Gateway with JWT tokens.

Concept Explanation (with slides):

Here‚Äôs the idea:

Users register & log in through the User Service.

On successful login, the User Service generates a JWT (JSON Web Token).

Clients send this token in the Authorization header.

The API Gateway checks the token before forwarding the request to downstream services.

This way:

Unauthenticated requests ‚Üí rejected at the gateway.

Authenticated users ‚Üí pass through and access services.

(Slide: Client ‚Üí API Gateway (JWT check) ‚Üí Booking/Hotel/Payment.)

2. Demo Walkthrough
Step 1 ‚Äî Add Dependencies (User Service)
In user-service/pom.xml:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-security</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-api</artifactId>
    <version>0.11.5</version>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-impl</artifactId>
    <version>0.11.5</version>
    <scope>runtime</scope>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-jackson</artifactId>
    <version>0.11.5</version>
    <scope>runtime</scope>
</dependency>
Step 2 ‚Äî Create User Model & AuthController
User.java

@Entity
public class User {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;
    private String username;
    private String password;
}
AuthController.java

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/auth")
public class AuthController {

    private final JwtUtil jwtUtil;

    public AuthController(JwtUtil jwtUtil) {
        this.jwtUtil = jwtUtil;
    }

    @PostMapping("/login")
    public ResponseEntity<Map<String, String>> login(@RequestBody Map<String, String> creds) {
        String username = creds.get("username");
        String password = creds.get("password");

        // ‚ö†Ô∏è In real-world: validate against DB + encrypt passwords
        if ("user".equals(username) && "pass".equals(password)) {
            String token = jwtUtil.generateToken(username);
            return ResponseEntity.ok(Map.of("token", token));
        }
        return ResponseEntity.status(401).build();
    }
}
JwtUtil.java

@Component
public class JwtUtil {

    private final String secret = "mysecretkey"; // move to config server later

    public String generateToken(String username) {
        return Jwts.builder()
                .setSubject(username)
                .setIssuedAt(new Date())
                .setExpiration(new Date(System.currentTimeMillis() + 3600 * 1000)) // 1h
                .signWith(SignatureAlgorithm.HS256, secret.getBytes())
                .compact();
    }

    public Claims validateToken(String token) {
        return Jwts.parser()
                .setSigningKey(secret.getBytes())
                .parseClaimsJws(token)
                .getBody();
    }
}
Step 3 ‚Äî Secure API Gateway with JWT
In api-gateway/pom.xml:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-security</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-api</artifactId>
    <version>0.11.5</version>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-impl</artifactId>
    <version>0.11.5</version>
    <scope>runtime</scope>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-jackson</artifactId>
    <version>0.11.5</version>
    <scope>runtime</scope>
</dependency>
JwtAuthenticationFilter.java

@Component
public class JwtAuthenticationFilter extends AbstractGatewayFilterFactory<JwtAuthenticationFilter.Config> {

    private final JwtUtil jwtUtil;

    public JwtAuthenticationFilter(JwtUtil jwtUtil) {
        super(Config.class);
        this.jwtUtil = jwtUtil;
    }

    @Override
    public GatewayFilter apply(Config config) {
        return (exchange, chain) -> {
            ServerHttpRequest request = exchange.getRequest();
            if (!request.getHeaders().containsKey(HttpHeaders.AUTHORIZATION)) {
                return unauthorized(exchange);
            }
            String token = request.getHeaders().getFirst(HttpHeaders.AUTHORIZATION).replace("Bearer ", "");
            try {
                jwtUtil.validateToken(token);
            } catch (Exception e) {
                return unauthorized(exchange);
            }
            return chain.filter(exchange);
        };
    }

    private Mono<Void> unauthorized(ServerWebExchange exchange) {
        exchange.getResponse().setStatusCode(HttpStatus.UNAUTHORIZED);
        return exchange.getResponse().setComplete();
    }

    public static class Config {}
}
In application.yml, secure routes:

spring:
  cloud:
    gateway:
      routes:
        - id: booking-service
          uri: lb://booking-service
          predicates:
            - Path=/booking/**
          filters:
            - JwtAuthenticationFilter
Step 4 ‚Äî Test Flow
Call API Gateway without token:

GET http://localhost:8080/booking/hotels
üëâ Response: 401 Unauthorized

Get JWT from login:

POST http://localhost:8080/user-service/auth/login
{
  "username": "user",
  "password": "pass"
}
üëâ Response: { "token": "eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIs..." }

Retry request with token:

GET http://localhost:8080/booking/hotels
Authorization: Bearer <token>
üëâ Success üéâ ‚Äî Hotels are returned.

3. Recap (on camera)
Today, we secured our API Gateway with JWT authentication.

The User Service issues JWT tokens on login.

The API Gateway validates tokens before routing requests.

Unauthorized users get blocked at the gateway.

In the next episode, we‚Äôll add role-based access control ‚Äî so normal users can book hotels, but only admins can manage hotels or view all bookings.

