üé• Episode 10 ‚Äî Securing Secrets with Spring Cloud Config
1. Narration Script (spoken style)
Intro (on camera):

Welcome back!
So far, our hotel booking system has user authentication and role-based access control.
But here‚Äôs a big issue: our JWT signing key, database credentials, and other sensitive configs are hardcoded in our services.
That‚Äôs a serious security risk.

Today, we‚Äôll fix this using Spring Cloud Config Server.
This will centralize our configuration and allow us to securely manage secrets for all microservices.

Concept Explanation (with slides):

Here‚Äôs the idea:

Instead of hardcoding secrets in application.yml, we‚Äôll move them to a Git repo or a Vault store.

The Spring Cloud Config Server fetches these configs.

Each microservice retrieves its configs dynamically at startup.

This way, we can rotate keys, change DB credentials, or update settings without rebuilding services.

Security benefit: secrets are not in source code, but stored in a central, secured location.

(Slide: Config Server in middle ‚Üí Services pulling configs ‚Üí Git/Vault as source.)

2. Demo Walkthrough
Step 1 ‚Äî Create Config Server
config-server/pom.xml

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-config-server</artifactId>
</dependency>
ConfigServerApplication.java

@SpringBootApplication
@EnableConfigServer
public class ConfigServerApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(ConfigServerApplication.class, args);
    }
}
application.yml

server:
  port: 8888

spring:
  cloud:
    config:
      server:
        git:
          uri: https://github.com/your-repo/hotel-config
          clone-on-start: true
üëâ Start the Config Server.

Step 2 ‚Äî Create Config Repository
In GitHub repo hotel-config/, create files like:

user-service.yml

jwt:
  secret: my-secret-from-config
spring:
  datasource:
    url: jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/userdb
    username: dbuser
    password: dbpass123
booking-service.yml

spring:
  datasource:
    url: jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/bookingdb
    username: dbuser
    password: dbpass123
Step 3 ‚Äî Configure Microservices to Use Config Server
In user-service/pom.xml:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-config</artifactId>
</dependency>
Add bootstrap.yml (loads before application.yml):

spring:
  application:
    name: user-service
  cloud:
    config:
      uri: http://localhost:8888
Update JwtUtil.java:

@Component
@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = "jwt")
public class JwtUtil {
    private String secret;

    public void setSecret(String secret) {
        this.secret = secret;
    }

    public String generateToken(String username, String role) {
        return Jwts.builder()
                .setSubject(username)
                .claim("role", role)
                .setIssuedAt(new Date())
                .setExpiration(new Date(System.currentTimeMillis() + 3600 * 1000))
                .signWith(SignatureAlgorithm.HS256, secret.getBytes())
                .compact();
    }

    public Claims validateToken(String token) {
        return Jwts.parser()
                .setSigningKey(secret.getBytes())
                .parseClaimsJws(token)
                .getBody();
    }
}
üëâ Now the JWT secret comes from Config Server, not hardcoded in code.

Step 4 ‚Äî Test Flow
Start Config Server (http://localhost:8888/user-service/default).
üëâ You‚Äôll see config values served as JSON.

Start User Service ‚Üí It pulls JWT secret + DB credentials from Config Server.

Login request works the same, but now secret is externally managed.

Step 5 ‚Äî Add Security for Config Server (Optional, Advanced)
You can secure Config Server itself with Spring Security:

application.yml

spring:
  security:
    user:
      name: configadmin
      password: configpass
Then in microservices‚Äô bootstrap.yml:

spring:
  cloud:
    config:
      uri: http://localhost:8888
      username: configadmin
      password: configpass
3. Recap (on camera)
Today, we secured our system by moving secrets out of code and into the Spring Cloud Config Server.

JWT keys, DB credentials, and service configs are externalized.

Microservices fetch configs dynamically at startup.

Config Server itself can be secured with authentication.

In the next episode, we‚Äôll cover Spring Cloud Bus ‚Äî so when configs change, all microservices can be updated automatically without restarts.

