This is a must-have for debugging and monitoring microservices because requests often hop between services, and without tracing, it‚Äôs hard to know where time is being spent or what failed.

üé• Episode 12 ‚Äî Distributed Tracing with Spring Cloud Sleuth + Zipkin
1. Narration Script (spoken style)
Intro (on camera):

Welcome back!
Our hotel booking system is now secure and dynamically configurable. But when a request flows through multiple services ‚Äî say, from User Service ‚Üí Booking Service ‚Üí Payment Service ‚Üí Notification Service ‚Äî how do we trace that request across the system?

Without visibility, debugging is a nightmare.
That‚Äôs where Spring Cloud Sleuth and Zipkin come in.

Today, I‚Äôll show you how to enable distributed tracing so we can see the full journey of a request across all our microservices.

Concept Explanation (with slides):

Sleuth adds trace IDs and span IDs to every log.

Trace ID ‚Üí represents one request across services.

Span ID ‚Üí represents a single hop inside one service.

Zipkin collects this data, so we can visualize latency, bottlenecks, and failures.

(Slide: Request ‚Üí API Gateway ‚Üí Booking ‚Üí Payment ‚Üí Notification, all logs share same trace ID.)

2. Demo Walkthrough
Step 1 ‚Äî Add Dependencies
In all microservices (pom.xml):

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-sleuth</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-sleuth-zipkin</artifactId>
</dependency>
Step 2 ‚Äî Run Zipkin
Run Zipkin using Docker:

docker run -d -p 9411:9411 openzipkin/zipkin
üëâ Access UI at: http://localhost:9411

Step 3 ‚Äî Configure Microservices
In application.yml of each service:

spring:
  zipkin:
    base-url: http://localhost:9411
  sleuth:
    sampler:
      probability: 1.0 # trace 100% of requests
Step 4 ‚Äî Trigger a Request
Let‚Äôs book a hotel via API Gateway:

POST http://localhost:8080/booking/reserve
Authorization: Bearer <user-token>
{
  "hotelId": 1,
  "userId": 1,
  "paymentMethod": "CREDIT_CARD"
}
üëâ Flow:

API Gateway ‚Üí Booking Service ‚Üí Payment Service ‚Üí Notification Service.

Sleuth automatically:

Adds traceId and spanId to logs.

Sends tracing data to Zipkin.

Step 5 ‚Äî View Traces in Zipkin
Open http://localhost:9411

Search by service name (e.g., booking-service).

View timeline:

API Gateway (entry point)

Booking Service (reservation logic)

Payment Service (processing payment)

Notification Service (sending confirmation)

üëâ You‚Äôll see the latency breakdown per service.

3. Recap (on camera)
Today, we added distributed tracing with Spring Cloud Sleuth and Zipkin.

Every request now has a trace ID shared across microservices.

We can see request flow and timing in Zipkin.

This helps us identify slow services and debug failures much faster.

In the next episode, we‚Äôll take tracing further with Spring Cloud Sleuth + Logs Correlation ‚Äî so we can follow a request not just in Zipkin, but also across service logs.

