Awesome üöÄ Let‚Äôs dive into Episode 14: Resilience with Hystrix (Circuit Breaker in Booking ‚Üí Payment flow).
This one is really fun because we‚Äôll simulate failures in the Payment Service and show how Hystrix protects our system from cascading failures.

üé• Episode 14 ‚Äî Resilience with Hystrix (Circuit Breaker Pattern)
1. Narration Script (spoken style)
Intro (on camera):

Welcome back!
So far, our hotel booking system works smoothly ‚Äî users can book hotels, make payments, and receive confirmations.

But what happens if the Payment Service goes down? ü§î
Right now, Booking Service would keep trying, causing delays and maybe even crashing.

That‚Äôs where Hystrix, the circuit breaker, comes in.
Today, I‚Äôll show you how to make our system fault-tolerant with Hystrix.

Concept Explanation (with slides):

The Circuit Breaker Pattern works just like an electric fuse.

If Payment Service is healthy ‚Üí calls go through.

If Payment Service fails too often ‚Üí the circuit opens, and requests fail fast.

After a timeout, the circuit goes into half-open state to test if the service is back.

This prevents one bad service from bringing the whole system down.

(Slide: Diagram ‚Üí Booking ‚Üí Payment (fails), Hystrix trips, fallback response.)

2. Demo Walkthrough
Step 1 ‚Äî Add Hystrix Dependency
In Booking Service pom.xml:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-hystrix</artifactId>
</dependency>
Step 2 ‚Äî Enable Hystrix
In Booking Service main class:

@SpringBootApplication
@EnableCircuitBreaker
public class BookingServiceApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(BookingServiceApplication.class, args);
    }
}
Step 3 ‚Äî Wrap Payment Calls with Hystrix
Suppose we call Payment Service via Feign.
In PaymentClient.java:

@FeignClient(name = "payment-service", fallback = PaymentFallback.class)
public interface PaymentClient {

    @PostMapping("/payments/process")
    String processPayment(@RequestBody PaymentRequest request);
}
Fallback implementation:

@Component
public class PaymentFallback implements PaymentClient {
    @Override
    public String processPayment(PaymentRequest request) {
        return "Payment Service is currently unavailable. Please try again later.";
    }
}
Step 4 ‚Äî Simulate Failure
Stop the Payment Service and try booking again:

POST http://localhost:8080/booking/reserve
{
  "hotelId": 1,
  "userId": 1,
  "paymentMethod": "CREDIT_CARD"
}
üëâ Response from Booking Service:

{
  "status": "FAILED",
  "message": "Payment Service is currently unavailable. Please try again later."
}
Instead of crashing or hanging, our system fails gracefully.

Step 5 ‚Äî Hystrix Dashboard (Optional)
Add Hystrix dashboard dependency to monitor circuits:

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-hystrix-dashboard</artifactId>
</dependency>
Enable dashboard:

@EnableHystrixDashboard
@SpringBootApplication
public class BookingServiceApplication { ... }
Run ‚Üí http://localhost:8080/hystrix
Enter stream: http://localhost:8080/actuator/hystrix.stream

