üé• Episode 15 ‚Äî Resilience with Resilience4j (Modern Circuit Breaker)
1. Narration Script (spoken style)
Intro (on camera):

Welcome back, engineers!
In the last episode, we added fault tolerance using Hystrix ‚Äî but Hystrix is now deprecated.

In modern Spring Cloud apps, the recommended approach is Resilience4j.
It‚Äôs faster, lighter, and fully compatible with Spring Boot.

Today, we‚Äôll migrate our circuit breaker logic from Hystrix to Resilience4j,
using the Booking ‚Üí Payment flow as our case study.

Concept Explanation (with slides):

Resilience4j provides several resilience patterns:

Circuit Breaker ‚Üí prevents cascading failures

Retry ‚Üí automatically retries failed calls

Rate Limiter ‚Üí controls request rate

Bulkhead ‚Üí isolates failures between threads

Think of it like Hystrix 2.0 ‚Äî modular, lightweight, and fully Java 8+ friendly.

(Slide: Side-by-side comparison ‚Äî Hystrix vs Resilience4j)

2. Demo Walkthrough
Step 1 ‚Äî Add Dependencies
In Booking Service pom.xml:

<dependency>
    <groupId>io.github.resilience4j</groupId>
    <artifactId>resilience4j-spring-boot3</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-aop</artifactId>
</dependency>
Step 2 ‚Äî Configure Circuit Breaker
In application.yml:

resilience4j:
  circuitbreaker:
    instances:
      paymentService:
        registerHealthIndicator: true
        slidingWindowSize: 5
        minimumNumberOfCalls: 3
        failureRateThreshold: 50
        waitDurationInOpenState: 10s
        permittedNumberOfCallsInHalfOpenState: 2
        automaticTransitionFromOpenToHalfOpenEnabled: true
  retry:
    instances:
      paymentService:
        maxAttempts: 3
        waitDuration: 2s
Step 3 ‚Äî Wrap Payment Call
In BookingService.java:

@Service
public class BookingService {

    private final PaymentClient paymentClient;

    public BookingService(PaymentClient paymentClient) {
        this.paymentClient = paymentClient;
    }

    @CircuitBreaker(name = "paymentService", fallbackMethod = "paymentFallback")
    @Retry(name = "paymentService")
    public String bookHotel(BookingRequest request) {
        return paymentClient.processPayment(request);
    }

    public String paymentFallback(BookingRequest request, Throwable ex) {
        return "Payment temporarily unavailable. Please try again later.";
    }
}
Step 4 ‚Äî Simulate Failure
Stop the Payment Service and call:

POST http://localhost:8080/booking/reserve
{
  "hotelId": 1,
  "userId": 1,
  "paymentMethod": "CREDIT_CARD"
}
Response:

{
  "status": "FAILED",
  "message": "Payment temporarily unavailable. Please try again later."
}
You‚Äôll see in logs that Resilience4j:

Retries 3 times

Then opens the circuit after consecutive failures

Falls back instantly until the Payment Service recovers

Step 5 ‚Äî Circuit Breaker Health
Hit the actuator endpoint:

GET http://localhost:8080/actuator/health
You‚Äôll see:

{
  "status": "UP",
  "components": {
    "circuitBreakers": {
      "details": {
        "paymentService": {
          "state": "OPEN"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
3. Recap (on camera)
Awesome work today!

We replaced Hystrix with Resilience4j ‚Äî a modern, lightweight, and production-grade library for resilience patterns.

It handles circuit breaking, retries, rate limiting, and more.

It integrates with Spring Boot Actuator for live health checks.

In the next episode, we‚Äôll improve our API Gateway experience with Spring Cloud Gateway filters ‚Äî adding authentication, rate limiting, and tracing at the edge.

