üé• Episode 16 ‚Äî Spring Cloud Gateway Filters: Authentication, Rate Limiting & Tracing at the Edge
üéôÔ∏è Narration Script (spoken like a YouTube tutorial)
Intro (on camera):

Welcome back, everyone!

So far, we‚Äôve built a powerful distributed system ‚Äî complete with discovery, fault tolerance, and tracing.

But all traffic still flows through one entry point ‚Äî our API Gateway.

Today, we‚Äôll make that gateway smarter.
We‚Äôll add:

Authentication filters (to block unauthorized users)

Rate limiting (to protect from traffic spikes)

Distributed tracing at the edge (to tag requests before they enter the system)

This is a huge step toward production-level readiness. Let‚Äôs go! üöÄ

üìò Concept Explanation (show slides / visuals)
Slide 1: "Gateway as the Entry Point"

The API Gateway acts as the front door for all our microservices.
It routes, filters, authenticates, logs, and enforces policies before requests hit internal services.

Slide 2: "Three Types of Filters"

Pre-Filters: run before routing (e.g., authentication, tracing)

Post-Filters: run after response (e.g., logging)

Global Filters: apply to all routes

Slide 3: ‚ÄúFlow Diagram‚Äù
Client ‚Üí Spring Cloud Gateway ‚Üí Booking / Payment / Notification

üíª Hands-On Demo
Step 1 ‚Äî Add Dependencies
pom.xml

<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-gateway</artifactId>
    </dependency>

    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-security</artifactId>
    </dependency>

    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.data</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-data-redis-reactive</artifactId>
    </dependency>

    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-actuator</artifactId>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
Step 2 ‚Äî Configure Routing and Rate Limiting
application.yml

spring:
  application:
    name: api-gateway
  cloud:
    gateway:
      routes:
        - id: booking-service
          uri: lb://BOOKING-SERVICE
          predicates:
            - Path=/booking/**
          filters:
            - name: RequestRateLimiter
              args:
                redis-rate-limiter.replenishRate: 5     # 5 requests per second
                redis-rate-limiter.burstCapacity: 10    # max burst
                key-resolver: "#{@ipKeyResolver}"

        - id: payment-service
          uri: lb://PAYMENT-SERVICE
          predicates:
            - Path=/payment/**
üí° Explanation on camera:

Here, each route defines URI, path predicate, and optional filters.
The rate limiter uses Redis to count requests per client IP ‚Äî we‚Äôll define that next.

Step 3 ‚Äî Implement Key Resolver for Rate Limiting
IpKeyResolver.java

@Component("ipKeyResolver")
public class IpKeyResolver implements KeyResolver {
    @Override
    public Mono<String> resolve(ServerWebExchange exchange) {
        return Mono.just(
            exchange.getRequest()
                    .getRemoteAddress()
                    .getAddress()
                    .getHostAddress()
        );
    }
}
üí° Explanation:

This tells the gateway:
‚ÄúRate-limit users based on their IP address.‚Äù
You could also limit by user ID or API key.

Step 4 ‚Äî Add Authentication Filter
AuthFilter.java

@Component
public class AuthFilter implements GlobalFilter, Ordered {

    private static final String AUTH_HEADER = "Authorization";

    @Override
    public Mono<Void> filter(ServerWebExchange exchange, GatewayFilterChain chain) {
        String token = exchange.getRequest().getHeaders().getFirst(AUTH_HEADER);

        if (token == null || !token.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
            exchange.getResponse().setStatusCode(HttpStatus.UNAUTHORIZED);
            return exchange.getResponse().setComplete();
        }

        // Example validation (in real life, decode JWT or call User Service)
        if (!token.equals("Bearer valid-token")) {
            exchange.getResponse().setStatusCode(HttpStatus.FORBIDDEN);
            return exchange.getResponse().setComplete();
        }

        return chain.filter(exchange);
    }

    @Override
    public int getOrder() {
        return -1; // run before routing
    }
}
üí° On camera:

Our filter checks for a Bearer token.
In production, this would call a User Service or JWT verifier.
For now, we simulate it with a simple check.

Step 5 ‚Äî Add Tracing Filter (Optional Sleuth Enhancement)
TracingFilter.java

@Component
public class TracingFilter implements GlobalFilter {
    private static final Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(TracingFilter.class);

    @Override
    public Mono<Void> filter(ServerWebExchange exchange, GatewayFilterChain chain) {
        String traceId = UUID.randomUUID().toString().substring(0, 8);
        exchange.getRequest().mutate()
                .header("X-Trace-Id", traceId)
                .build();
        log.info("New request traceId={} path={}", traceId, exchange.getRequest().getURI());
        return chain.filter(exchange);
    }
}
üí° Explanation:

This assigns a unique traceId at the gateway level ‚Äî
every downstream service (Booking, Payment, etc.) receives it in headers and includes it in their Sleuth logs.

Step 6 ‚Äî Test Everything
Run:

docker run -d -p 6379:6379 redis
Then test routes:

‚úÖ Authorized Request:

curl -H "Authorization: Bearer valid-token" http://localhost:8080/booking/reserve
‚ùå Unauthorized Request:

curl http://localhost:8080/booking/reserve
‚Üí Returns 401 Unauthorized

‚ö° Rate Limit Test:
Hit endpoint rapidly ‚Üí get 429 Too Many Requests

üß† Recap (on camera)
Today, we transformed our gateway from a simple router into a policy enforcement engine.

‚úÖ Added authentication with custom filters

‚ö° Added Redis-based rate limiting

üß© Added trace headers for distributed observability

These features make your system more secure, scalable, and traceable at the edge.

In the next episode, we‚Äôll look at centralized logging with the ELK Stack,
so we can view all these gateway and service logs in one place.

