üé¨ EPISODE 20 ‚Äî Centralized Logging with ELK Stack (Elasticsearch, Logstash, Kibana)
üéôÔ∏è Intro (spoken on camera)
Welcome back!
By now, we‚Äôve built a full cloud-native hotel booking system ‚Äî complete with discovery, config, tracing, and gateway.

But when something breaks, where do you look?
Logs.
And when you have multiple microservices, those logs are everywhere.

Today, we‚Äôll solve that by setting up centralized logging using the ELK Stack ‚Äî Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana.

üìò Concept (show diagram)
Slide 1:
‚ÄúEach microservice logs locally ‚Üí Logstash ships logs ‚Üí Elasticsearch indexes them ‚Üí Kibana visualizes them.‚Äù

Slide 2:
Flow Diagram:

Hotel / Booking / Payment / Notification
        ‚Üì
     Logstash
        ‚Üì
  Elasticsearch
        ‚Üì
      Kibana
üíª Hands-On Setup
Step 1 ‚Äî Start ELK via Docker Compose

Create docker-compose.yml:

version: '3.7'
services:
  elasticsearch:
    image: docker.elastic.co/elasticsearch/elasticsearch:7.17.9
    container_name: elasticsearch
    environment:
      - discovery.type=single-node
    ports:
      - 9200:9200

  logstash:
    image: docker.elastic.co/logstash/logstash:7.17.9
    container_name: logstash
    ports:
      - 5000:5000
    volumes:
      - ./logstash.conf:/usr/share/logstash/pipeline/logstash.conf

  kibana:
    image: docker.elastic.co/kibana/kibana:7.17.9
    container_name: kibana
    ports:
      - 5601:5601
Step 2 ‚Äî Logstash Config

Create logstash.conf:

input {
  tcp {
    port => 5000
    codec => json_lines
  }
}

output {
  elasticsearch {
    hosts => ["elasticsearch:9200"]
    index => "springcloud-logs-%{+YYYY.MM.dd}"
  }
}
Step 3 ‚Äî Send Logs from Microservices

In each Spring Boot service, update application.yml:

logging:
  level:
    root: INFO
  appender:
    console:
      enabled: true
  logstash:
    enabled: true
Add dependency:

<dependency>
    <groupId>net.logstash.logback</groupId>
    <artifactId>logstash-logback-encoder</artifactId>
    <version>7.4</version>
</dependency>
And add Logstash appender in logback-spring.xml:

<appender name="LOGSTASH" class="net.logstash.logback.appender.LogstashTcpSocketAppender">
    <destination>localhost:5000</destination>
    <encoder class="net.logstash.logback.encoder.LogstashEncoder"/>
</appender>

<root level="INFO">
    <appender-ref ref="LOGSTASH"/>
    <appender-ref ref="CONSOLE"/>
</root>
Step 4 ‚Äî Visualize in Kibana

Open http://localhost:5601

Create index pattern: springcloud-logs-*

Explore all microservice logs in one view üéâ

üß† Recap
You now have centralized logging across all services.
It‚Äôs searchable, visual, and production-ready.
In the next episode, we‚Äôll go one step further ‚Äî metrics & dashboards with Prometheus and Grafana.

üß© Slides:
‚ÄúEpisode 20: Centralized Logging with ELK Stack‚Äù

Flow Diagram

Kibana Dashboard example

Summary checklist

