Learners can aggregate, analyze, and visualize logs for all microservices.

üé¨ EPISODE 21 ‚Äî Monitoring and Metrics with Prometheus & Grafana
üéôÔ∏è Intro
Welcome back!
Logs show what happened ‚Äî but metrics show how your system behaves over time.

In this episode, we‚Äôll integrate Prometheus and Grafana to monitor service health, performance, and throughput.

üìò Concept
Slide 1:
Spring Boot ‚Üí Actuator exposes /actuator/metrics
Prometheus scrapes ‚Üí stores time-series data
Grafana visualizes dashboards

üíª Hands-On
Step 1 ‚Äî Add Dependencies

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-actuator</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.micrometer</groupId>
    <artifactId>micrometer-registry-prometheus</artifactId>
</dependency>
Step 2 ‚Äî Enable Prometheus Endpoint
application.yml

management:
  endpoints:
    web:
      exposure:
        include: health,info,prometheus
Step 3 ‚Äî Run Prometheus & Grafana
docker-compose.yml

version: '3.7'
services:
  prometheus:
    image: prom/prometheus
    ports:
      - 9090:9090
    volumes:
      - ./prometheus.yml:/etc/prometheus/prometheus.yml

  grafana:
    image: grafana/grafana
    ports:
      - 3000:3000
prometheus.yml

scrape_configs:
  - job_name: 'spring-cloud-services'
    static_configs:
      - targets:
          - 'host.docker.internal:8081'
          - 'host.docker.internal:8082'
          - 'host.docker.internal:8083'
Step 4 ‚Äî Create Dashboards

Open Grafana ‚Üí http://localhost:3000

Add Prometheus data source

Import dashboard ID: 4701 (Spring Boot Metrics)

Visualize CPU, memory, request rate, latency

üß† Recap
Now you can monitor your microservices in real time!
Prometheus collects metrics, Grafana visualizes them, and you get alerts when something goes wrong.

Next, we‚Äôll wrap the series with deployment ‚Äî Docker + Kubernetes for real-world scalability.

‚úÖ Outcome
Learners can:

Collect Spring metrics

Create Grafana dashboards

Visualize and alert on service performance

üé¨ EPISODE 22 ‚Äî Deploying Microservices to Kubernetes (Production)
üéôÔ∏è Intro
This is it ‚Äî the grand finale!

We‚Äôve built, traced, logged, and monitored everything.
Now let‚Äôs deploy our Hotel Booking System to Kubernetes ‚Äî the final step to make it production-ready.

üìò Concept
Slide 1:
Microservices ‚Üí Containerized ‚Üí Managed by Kubernetes
Slide 2:
Kubernetes Components:

Pods ‚Üí your Spring Boot containers

Services ‚Üí expose endpoints

ConfigMap & Secrets ‚Üí externalize config

Ingress ‚Üí entry point (like API Gateway)

üíª Hands-On
Step 1 ‚Äî Dockerize Each Service

Create a Dockerfile in each project:

FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim
ARG JAR_FILE=target/*.jar
COPY ${JAR_FILE} app.jar
ENTRYPOINT ["java","-jar","/app.jar"]
Build images:

mvn clean package -DskipTests
Step 2 ‚Äî Create Kubernetes Manifests

Example: hotel-service.yaml

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: hotel-service
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: hotel-service
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: hotel-service
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: hotel-service
          ports:
            - containerPort: 8081
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: hotel-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: hotel-service
  ports:
    - port: 8081
      targetPort: 8081
Repeat for other services (Booking, Payment, etc.)

Step 3 ‚Äî Deploy

kubectl apply -f hotel-service.yaml
kubectl get pods
Step 4 ‚Äî Expose via API Gateway
Use Ingress:

apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: api-gateway-ingress
spec:
  rules:
    - host: booking-system.local
      http:
        paths:
          - path: /
            pathType: Prefix
            backend:
              service:
                name: api-gateway
                port:
                  number: 8080
Step 5 ‚Äî Test
Access:

http://booking-system.local/booking/reserve
üß† Recap
Congratulations ‚Äî you‚Äôve just deployed a complete, production-ready Spring Cloud microservices system to Kubernetes!

You now understand:
‚úÖ Spring Cloud fundamentals
‚úÖ Service discovery, resilience, tracing
‚úÖ Centralized logging and metrics
‚úÖ Scalable cloud deployment

This is a real-world architecture you can proudly show in your portfolio. üöÄ

