üî• Perfect ‚Äî here‚Äôs your EPISODE 23 (Bonus) ‚Äî the grand finale of your Spring Cloud Hotel Booking System YouTube series.

This episode ties everything together with a real CI/CD pipeline, showing how code goes from GitHub ‚Üí Docker Hub ‚Üí Kubernetes automatically.
This is where theory meets DevOps reality.

üé¨ EPISODE 23 ‚Äî CI/CD Pipeline: GitHub Actions + Docker Hub + Kubernetes Deployment
üéôÔ∏è Intro (on camera)
Welcome back, everyone ‚Äî and congratulations on making it this far! üéâ

You‚Äôve built and deployed a full Spring Cloud microservices system: Config, Eureka, Gateway, Tracing, ELK, Prometheus, Grafana, and Kubernetes.

But right now, deployments are manual.
Every time we make a code change, we rebuild images, push to Docker Hub, and redeploy.

In this final bonus episode, we‚Äôll automate everything ‚Äî using GitHub Actions for CI/CD.

After today, each time you push to your repo, GitHub will:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Build your project
2Ô∏è‚É£ Create a Docker image
3Ô∏è‚É£ Push it to Docker Hub
4Ô∏è‚É£ Automatically deploy the new version to your Kubernetes cluster üöÄ

üìò Concept Explanation (show slides)
Slide 1:
‚ÄúCI/CD Pipeline Flow‚Äù

Git Commit ‚Üí GitHub Actions ‚Üí Build ‚Üí Docker Hub ‚Üí Kubernetes Cluster
Slide 2:
Stages:

Continuous Integration ‚Äì Build + Test

Continuous Delivery ‚Äì Push Docker Image

Continuous Deployment ‚Äì Apply to K8s automatically

Slide 3:
Diagram:
Developer ‚Üí GitHub ‚Üí (GitHub Actions Workflow) ‚Üí Docker Hub ‚Üí Kubernetes (kubectl apply)

üíª Hands-On Setup
üß© Step 1 ‚Äî Prerequisites
You‚Äôll need:

A GitHub repo (public or private)

A Docker Hub account

Access to your Kubernetes cluster (minikube or cloud)

GitHub repository secrets configured:

DOCKER_USERNAME

DOCKER_PASSWORD

KUBE_CONFIG (your base64-encoded kubeconfig)

üß© Step 2 ‚Äî Create GitHub Workflow File
Create file:
üìÇ .github/workflows/deploy.yml

name: CI/CD Pipeline

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build-and-deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Checkout code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Set up JDK 17
        uses: actions/setup-java@v4
        with:
          java-version: '17'
          distribution: 'temurin'

      - name: Build with Maven
        run: mvn clean package -DskipTests

      - name: Build Docker image
        run: docker build -t ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/hotel-service:${{ github.run_number }} .

      - name: Log in to Docker Hub
        run: echo "${{ secrets.DOCKER_PASSWORD }}" | docker login -u "${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}" --password-stdin

      - name: Push Docker image
        run: docker push ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/hotel-service:${{ github.run_number }}

      - name: Set up kubectl
        run: |
          echo "${{ secrets.KUBE_CONFIG }}" | base64 --decode > $HOME/.kube/config

      - name: Deploy to Kubernetes
        run: |
          kubectl set image deployment/hotel-service hotel-service=${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/hotel-service:${{ github.run_number }}
          kubectl rollout status deployment/hotel-service
üß† Explanation (on camera)
Every time we push to the main branch:
‚úÖ GitHub builds the Spring Boot project
‚úÖ Packages a Docker image
‚úÖ Pushes it to Docker Hub
‚úÖ Uses kubectl to update the deployment image
‚úÖ Waits for rollout to finish

So within minutes, your Kubernetes cluster runs the latest code automatically.

üß© Step 3 ‚Äî Add Versioning to Other Services
Each microservice (Booking, Payment, Notification, etc.) gets its own workflow file ‚Äî just change the names and image tags.

üß© Step 4 ‚Äî Verify the Pipeline
Push a commit:

git add .
git commit -m "Update booking service endpoint"
git push origin main
Then go to GitHub ‚Üí Actions tab ‚Üí watch your workflow execute:
üü¢ Build ‚Üí üü¢ Push ‚Üí üü¢ Deploy ‚Üí üü¢ Rollout complete

In a few minutes, your app updates automatically in Kubernetes! üî•

üß† Recap
Today, you learned how to:

Build an automated CI/CD pipeline with GitHub Actions

Publish Docker images to Docker Hub

Deploy changes to Kubernetes automatically

This makes your Spring Cloud microservices truly production-grade ‚Äî continuously integrated, delivered, and deployed.

